column8: C1. Climate variation is normal, so why should this be a problem?
column9: C2. Climate change will not be a problem because there will be technological solutions available.
column10: C3. I think it is safe to say climate change is here.
column11: C4. The negative effects of the climate change on local commerce should be taken into account.
column12: C5. I don't trust what scientists say about climate change.
column13: C6. I don't trust what I hear about climate change from government.
column14: C7. It's difficult to trust what comes out in the media on the issue of climate change.
column15: C8. There is not enough information to definitively say that climate change is real.
column16: C9. There is not enough information to definitively establish if the link between the agri-food system and climate change is real.
column17: C10. There's not much point in me doing anything to make agriculture more sustainable. No-one else is going to.
column18: C11. I don't know what to do. I'm very concerned and would like to do something, but I don't have a realistic shortlist of things that would really make a difference.
column19: C12. I believe that the difference we can have as an individual, in Switzerland, is so minimal that our actions are worthless.
column20: C13. I'm not going to do anything to address the impacts of the agri-food system because it is not a major issue.
column21: C14. I am happy to pay a higher price for local or organic food products
column22: C15. Eating sustainably is too expensive, and only wealthy people can afford it
column23: C16. Agricultural subsidies should promote sustainable, pesticide and antibiotic-free production.
column24: C17. Sustainable agriculture increases prices and harms consumer freedom. The production should be adapted to what people demand.
column25: C18. “Food accessibility (price) and security (availability) is NOT COMPATIBLE with a sustainable food system”
column26: C19. Strong regulation of food production will eventually damage our economic relationship with other countries
column27: C20. We should develop short distribution channels and support local production instead of supporting big agrifood corporations
column28: C21. We need to focus on adaptation actions that are concerned with the economic future of the country.
column29: C22. “Actions on the food system in Switzerland will lead to increased imports and shift of the pollution abroad”
column30: C23. We need actions to protect inhabitants and the biodiversity from harmful pesticide.
column31: C24. As long as we use animals in agriculture, it cannot be sustainable
column32: C25. We need to deal with the water pollution issue through measures such as reducing fertilizer and pesticide use.
column33: C26. Banning pesticides might help the local biodiversity but decreases our food production capacity and autonomy
column34: C27. Agriculture is already very sustainable. Swiss farmers are on the right track
column35: C28. “Intensive food production can go along with the protection of the environment and health”
column36: C29. “Farmers already suffer enough from strict rules and paperwork. Family farmers should have more liberties”
column37: C30. The main focus of planning for adaptation should be to prepare the food system for extreme weather events, such as drought and flooding.
column38: C31. Products that use environmentally harmful ingredients, such as palm oil, should be taxed in the same way as tobacco products.
column39: C32. If Switzerland reduces greenhouse gases of its food system it won't make a difference.
column40: C33. It is important to plan for migration by people displaced by malnutrition and famine.
column41: C34. We should focus on protecting human systems rather than environmental ecosystems.
column42: C35. The Swiss food system depends on imports from other countries, and it is in our interest to help find an effective global solution.
column43: C36. Some communities are more affected than others by the global agri-food system, but this is not a priority issue.
column44: C37. The Swiss food system is particularly vulnerable to climate change, and it is in our interest to help find an effective global solution.
column45: C38. Climate warming will ultimately benefit food production globally as plants better growth in higher temperature
column46: C39. It is NOT necessary to engage with the community when deciding what are the most important issues for planning for food system changes.
column47: C40. Planning for food system adaptation needs a holistic approach, considering a whole range of issues, instead of focussing on individual issues.
column48: C41. There is no urgent need to prepare for an increase in illness and death caused by intensive use of pesticides/antibiotics
column49: C42. The community should be involved in discussions about food system adaptation.
column50: C43. It is important to support smal land local farming as they have the fewest resources to deal with impacts of climate change.
